370","Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland"},"da":{"1358–1378":"1358–1378","1358–1444":"1358–1444","1378–1444":"1378–1444","1338–1360":"1338–1360","1338–1370":"1338–1370","1338":"1338","1358":"1358","1378":"1378","1444":"1444","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayr, Ayrshire, Skotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Skotland"},"nl":{"1358–1378":"1358–1378","1358–1444":"1358–1444","1378–1444":"1378–1444","1338–1360":"1338–1360","1338–1370":"1338–1370","1338":"1338","1358":"1358","1378":"1378","1444":"1444","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayr, Ayrshire, Schotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Schotland"},"en":{"1358–1378":"1358–1378","1358–1444":"1358–1444","1378–1444":"1378–1444","1338–1360":"1338–1360","1338–1370":"1338–1370","1338":"1338","1358":"1358","1378":"1378","1444":"1444","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Currie","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Currie in Midlothian, first recorded in this form in 1230. It is derived from Gaelic <i>curraigh</i>, dative case of <i>currach</i> ‘wet plain, marsh’.","Scottish: habitational name from Corrie in Dumfriesshire or another place so named (see   Corrie  ).","Scottish form of Irish   Curry   or, in Arran, an Anglicized form of <b>Mac Mhuirich</b> (see   McMurray  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Corrie","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from any of the places in Arran, Dumfries, and elsewhere, named Corrie, from Gaelic <i>coire</i> ‘cauldron’, applied to a circular hanging valley on a mountain. The Corrie family, on record from the late 12th cent., were tenants of the Bruce lordship of Annandale in the Middle Ages.","Scottish: shortened form of   McCorry   ‘son of Godfrey’. See also   Curry  ,   McGorry  .","English and Scottish: topographic name denoting someone who lived ‘(at the) shepherd's hut’, Middle English <i>cori</i>. Alternatively, a variant of   Currey  ."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When David Currie was born in 1358, in Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland, his father, Sir David Currie, was 20 and his mother, Lady Jane Currie, was 20. He had at least 1 son with Lady Herries. He died in 1378, in his hometown, at the age of 20."},"et":{"1358–1378":"1358–1378","1358–1444":"1358–1444","1378–1444":"1378–1444","1338–1360":"1338–1360","1338–1370":"1338–1370","1338":"1338","1358":"1358","1378":"1378","1444":"1444","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1358–1378":"1358–1378","1358–1444":"1358–1444","1378–1444":"1378–1444","1338–1360":"1338–1360","1338–1370":"1338–1370","1338":"1338","1358":"1358","1378":"1378","1444":"1444","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayr, Ayrshire, Scotland","Ayrshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotla